<p>Staple uses a global configuration file called <span class="code">application.ini</span>. 
The <span class="code">application.ini</span> file holds many settings that change how the 
application connects to a database, whether to use headers and footers, or how authentication
will take place. You can use the sample file below to get started. You will of course have to
customize it to fit your needs. Keep reading for a description on each setting.</p>

<h3>Sample Config</h3>
<pre>
[application]
<b>public_location</b> = <em>'/staple/public/'</em>

[page]
<b>header</b> = <i>MODULES_ROOT</i><em>'header.php'</em>
<b>footer</b> = <i>MODULES_ROOT</i><em>'footer.php'</em>

[db]
<b>autoconnect</b> = 0 <u>;Not yet implemented</u>
<b>host</b> = <em>'localhost'</em>
<b>username</b> = <em>'username'</em>
<b>password</b> = <em>'password'</em>
<b>db</b> = <em>'databasename'</em>

[auth]
<b>enabled</b> = 1
<b>adapter</b> = <em>'Staple_DBAuthAdapter'</em>
<b>controller</b> = <em>'accountController'</em>
<b>authtable</b> = <em>'accounts'</em>
<b>uidfield</b> = <em>'username'</em>
<b>pwfield</b> = <em>'password'</em>
<b>rolefield</b> = <em>'accountType'</em>
<b>pwenctype</b> = <em>'SHA1'</em>
<b>allowedRoute[]</b> = <em>'index/splash'</em> <u>;Not yet implemented</u>

[email]
<b>html</b> = 1
<b>from</b> = <em>'no-reply@staplecode.org'</em>
<b>bcc</b> = <em>''</em>
<b>server</b> = <em>''</em>
<b>template</b> = <i>MODULES_ROOT</i><em>'email/template.html'</em>

[errors]
<b>devmode</b> = 0
</pre>

